snippet.textDisplay:
May he rest in peace. There's nothing worse or scarier than a doctor looking you in the eyes and saying to you "there's nothing more I can do for you." That moment of being face to face with your own mortality is something nobody should experience at such a young age. When I got sick I was 24 years old. Diagnosed with an autoimmune Disease called FSGS. I was told that there was no hope. Advised to fill out my advanced directive, living will, & advise my family on my final wishes. That was a horrible thing to have to do so young. I refused to accept defeat until my last breath, I fought. I can't believe it some days. I managed to beat the odds. Every doctor I saw gave the same prognosis. They all told me there was no way I would live to see my daughters grow up. To just make peace with that reality. It would make the process easier to go through. I refused! Not only did I live, I went into remission! Even the doctors were surprised. No words of apology for basically telling me to give up & accept death. My words to anybody out there who's struggling with a diagnosis they're told means certain death, don't give up! Doctors can only practice medicine, hence why they call it practicing medicine. Everybody is different, every version of the disease is different, & the way to fix each person is different. You just may be the one that beats the odds! So fight for that right until your final breath! Stay positive because in my case it's proven to be the best medicine I received!
Sending out heading vibes to anyone that needs them! 💕

I am so sad he passed, but I am so happy he lived 4 years longer just to prove so many of us who thought of giving up for so much less in our lifes that even that is possible. I think there is some really heavy component in setting goals and may it be something like the birthday or a wedding or anything else in your close friend circle and familiy.

Now my grandmother wasn't terminal sick, but she had her up and downs and survived 2 World Wars and wanted to die in many Winters to the point where she was like 99 years old and my Dad told her she couldn't die in Witnertime because then all the other old people in my extent familiy would die as well and getting a bit confused when dehydrated in this olda ge she asked her Son my father how old she was then and as he answered 99 she said sth like "Then I am going to be 100" and she turned 100 the next year and died in June peacefully.

Sadly she never saw me getting married which was also one of her wishes, but I feel like I see similiarties when I hear off people who know how little time they have left and say "I want to see the birth of my (great-great-grand)child, my sibblings married or sth.
